  abstract = {As well as holding a vast store of long-term memories, the human brain creates short-term memories that last only a few seconds and are essential for performing tasks such as adding two numbers or comparing the attractiveness of two faces. We know that only a limited amount of information can be stored in short-term memory, but whether we store high-quality representations of a small number of items, or a potentially infinite number of 'low resolution' items is the subject of much debate. A new study of visual working memory resolves the matter in favour of the 'high resolution' option: short-term information storage does not discard quality in favour of quantity, but stores a relatively small number of objects, as discrete fixed-resolution representations.},
